keep in touch with him.

150
00:07:04,158 --> 00:07:07,560
I don't even know
if he is alive, to be honest.

151
00:07:09,661 --> 00:07:12,230
AMY:
There's this guy.

152
00:07:12,265 --> 00:07:18,938
He is some kind of, like,
cop or investigator.

153
00:07:18,973 --> 00:07:21,891
Just a real tough, rough dude.

154
00:07:21,926 --> 00:07:24,775
He's constantly on patrol.

155
00:07:24,810 --> 00:07:29,214
And I'm getting that he was
some kind of grandfather figure

156
00:07:29,249 --> 00:07:30,781
or father figure.

157
00:07:30,816 --> 00:07:32,650
Someone
that's here now?

158
00:07:32,651 --> 00:07:33,651
Yes.

159
00:07:33,686 --> 00:07:35,320
He loves them.

160
00:07:35,321 --> 00:07:37,754
Right then,
I realized that dead man

161
00:07:37,789 --> 00:07:40,757
wanted to protect
the residents of the home.

162
00:07:40,792 --> 00:07:44,763
But there's, like, times
where he's seeing things

163
00:07:44,798 --> 00:07:49,466
that he doesn't agree with
or doesn't like,

164
00:07:49,501 --> 00:07:52,037
and that's when [snaps]
he'll sometimes just snap.

165
00:07:52,072 --> 00:07:53,937
But thanks to his bad temper,

166
00:07:53,972 --> 00:07:57,609
I think he was probably doing
more harm than good.

167
00:07:57,644 --> 00:08:00,712
Does he express that
in any way?

168
00:08:00,713 --> 00:08:04,550
He might influence you, like,
to feel angry for no reason.

169
00:08:04,585 --> 00:08:07,986
And then I just see, like,
black and yelling,

170
00:08:08,021 --> 00:08:09,087
which is his temper.

171
00:08:11,056 --> 00:08:12,374
NARRATOR: Next...

172
00:08:12,409 --> 00:08:13,868
This is unheard of.

173
00:08:13,903 --> 00:08:15,498
...secrets are exposed.

174
00:08:15,533 --> 00:08:17,094
I know she was murdered.

175
00:08:17,095 --> 00:08:19,848
NARRATOR: And in our second
investigation...

176
00:08:19,883 --> 00:08:22,601
I'm gonna take my kids
and walk out that door.

177
00:08:22,636 --> 00:08:24,587
...evil is unleashed.

178
00:08:24,622 --> 00:08:26,503
It hurts so **** bad.

179
00:08:26,538 --> 00:08:29,675
You're not welcome here anymore.
You have to go.

180
00:08:41,587 --> 00:08:44,288
STEVE:
From the moment it was built,

181
00:08:44,323 --> 00:08:46,925
Tom and Joanna's house
was plagued with tragedy.

182
00:08:46,960 --> 00:08:49,528
A couple of years after
the original owner moved in,

183
00:08:49,563 --> 00:08:52,729
he lost his wife
and two infant kids.

184
00:08:52,764 --> 00:08:55,599
But as terrible as that was,
it was no excuse

185
00:08:55,634 --> 00:08:59,105
for what he was accused of doing
after he got remarried.

186
00:09:10,348 --> 00:09:11,716
James and Harriet Lanfear,

187
00:09:11,751 --> 00:09:14,119
they got brought up
on charges of child abuse.

188
00:09:14,154 --> 00:09:15,719
This is 1860.

189
00:09:15,754 --> 00:09:18,757
Were a lot of cases
even brought to trial?

190
00:09:18,792 --> 00:09:19,690
This is unheard of.

191
00:09:19,691 --> 00:09:20,657
It just doesn't happen.

192
00:09:20,692 --> 00:09:22,192
And make it
even more interesting

193
00:09:22,227 --> 00:09:25,130
is the people who's bringing
the complaint.

194
00:09:25,165 --> 00:09:26,564
It's his own family.

195
00:09:26,565 --> 00:09:29,801
This is a very well-respected
family in town.

196
00:09:29,836 --> 00:09:31,235
This is a time period

197
00:09:31,270 --> 00:09:33,772
where everybody's
family business

198
00:09:33,807 --> 00:09:36,240
was their own
and no one else's,

199
00:09:36,275 --> 00:09:38,209
so the abuse
had to have been horrendous.

200
00:09:38,210 --> 00:09:41,596
All right, so,
she got a severe whipping

201
00:09:41,631 --> 00:09:44,983
and an application
of a hot flatiron

202
00:09:45,018 --> 00:09:46,752
on one of
the child's limbs.

203
00:09:46,787 --> 00:09:48,085
That's pretty bad.

204
00:09:48,120 --> 00:09:50,188
So, now, what wound up happening
at the trial?

205
00:09:50,223 --> 00:09:51,624
They were acquitted.

206
00:10:00,399 --> 00:10:04,035
AMY:
I see this, like, black thing.

207
00:10:04,070 --> 00:10:06,303
In life, it was a man.

208
00:10:06,338 --> 00:10:09,541
Now he's, like,
turning into a shadowy thing.

209
00:10:11,076 --> 00:10:13,145
He's like a stalker.

210
00:10:19,518 --> 00:10:24,357
MATTHEW: Do you have any idea
about his life?

211
00:10:24,392 --> 00:10:26,424
He goes all over the house,

212
00:10:26,459 --> 00:10:29,694
so I'm thinking
that he lived here.

213
00:10:30,862 --> 00:10:33,265
AMY: No matter where I went
on the property,

214
00:10:33,300 --> 00:10:34,865
that stalker followed.

215
00:10:34,900 --> 00:10:38,069
At first, I thought he was more
of a nuisance than a threat,

216
00:10:38,070 --> 00:10:39,436
but those feelings changed

217
00:10:39,471 --> 00:10:41,807
as soon as I met
one of his many victims.

218
00:10:46,044 --> 00:10:48,579
Yes.

219
00:10:48,614 --> 00:10:51,449
I see the little girl.
Yes.

220
00:10:51,484 --> 00:10:54,318
She's a living person,

221
00:10:54,353 --> 00:10:57,689
and there's a dead little girl
here as well.

222
00:10:57,724 --> 00:11:01,093
I know she was murdered
by the stalker.

223
00:11:01,128 --> 00:11:04,463
She's here to warn the living
about him.

224
00:11:04,498 --> 00:11:06,265
I think he killed
the dead girl,

225
00:11:07,766 --> 00:11:11,603
and I think he wants to kill
this girl.

226
00:11:15,641 --> 00:11:18,377
STEVE: By the late 1800s,
Tom and Joanna's property

227
00:11:18,412 --> 00:11:19,943
had already seen
a lot of misery.

228
00:11:19,978 --> 00:11:23,114
And according to a descendant
of another former owner,

229
00:11:23,115 --> 00:11:25,151
things were only gonna
get worse.

230
00:11:35,894 --> 00:11:38,430
Now, Dennis, what I found
interesting was that...

231
00:11:38,465 --> 00:11:42,899
...there was more than death,
as far as tragedy for this family. - Yes.

232
00:11:42,934 --> 00:11:47,539
Thomas' oldest son, Thomas,
married his first cousin.

233
00:11:47,574 --> 00:11:51,943
So Thomas Sr.
disowned his son.

234
00:11:51,978 --> 00:11:53,443
Wow.

235
00:11:53,478 --> 00:11:57,649
But Thomas also had children
that were very devoted to him.

236
00:11:57,684 --> 00:11:59,518
One of them was Edward.

237
00:12:00,853 --> 00:12:04,189
They were very close.
They were both firemen.

238
00:12:04,224 --> 00:12:06,423
He was
the next oldest son,

239
00:12:06,458 --> 00:12:11,695
but he also died
at a very young age of 43.

240
00:12:11,730 --> 00:12:16,435
He suffered over the last
couple years of his life.

241
00:12:16,470 --> 00:12:18,137
Okay.

242
00:12:24,777 --> 00:12:27,747
AMY: This angry guy
in the basement...

243
00:12:31,150 --> 00:12:36,756
he felt very, very ill.

244
00:12:40,392 --> 00:12:44,329
Can you tell anything about
who he was when he was alive?

245
00:12:44,364 --> 00:12:46,797
I think he lived here.

246
00:12:46,832 --> 00:12:52,638
He was a pretty private guy,
got sick in his 40s.

247
00:12:55,273 --> 00:12:57,977
I'm always trying to understand
the motivation

248
00:12:58,012 --> 00:12:59,710
behind a dead person's behavior.

249
00:12:59,745 --> 00:13:01,964
One way I do this
is by experiencing

250
00:13:01,999 --> 00:13:03,924
in a physical way
their emotions.

251
00:13:03,959 --> 00:13:05,815
And using this technique
on that man,

252
00:13:05,850 --> 00:13:09,154
I quickly identified the source
of his anger issues.

